//  Agent Profiles & Model assignments
//  1. Sisyphus: The Sociable Lead
// **Role:** Orchestrator, Task Delegator, Communication Hub.
// **Model:** `z-ai/glm-4.7`
// Sisyphus is the developer who knows everyone, goes everywhere, and gets things done through communication and coordination. He talks to other agents, understands context across the whole codebase, delegates work intelligently, and maintains the "state" of the project.
// **Why GLM-4.7?**
// Sisyphus requires a model with exceptional **logical consistency** and **instruction following**. The Zhipu GLM series is historically famous for hard logic benchmarks and rigid adherence to complex formatting rules. Sisyphus has a prompt over 1,000 lines long; GLM-4.7 has the stability to read that prompt and execute the orchestration loop without "getting bored" or hallucinating new tool formats. It acts as the steady hand guiding the project.
//  2. Hephaestus: The Context Architect
// **Role:** Deep Coder, Builder, Large-Scale Refactorer.
// **Model:** `moonshotai/kimi-k2.5`
// Hephaestus is the developer who stays in their room coding all day. You give them a massive feature request involving 30 files, and they need to hold all that context in their head at once to ensure the build compiles.
// **Why Kimi k2.5?**
// Hephaestus normally requires a "Codex" class model. In your environment, **Kimi** fills this role perfectly because of its massive **context window** and high fidelity in code retention. Kimi models are optimized for long-document understanding. When Hephaestus needs to refactor a module, Kimi can "see" the entire module at once, ensuring that a change in File A doesn't break a dependency in File Z. It is the builder who doesn't forget.
//  3. Oracle: The Source of Truth
// **Role:** High-Level Architecture, Truth Verification, Complex Reasoning.
// **Model:** `google/gemini-3-pro-preview`
// Oracle is the consultant you hire when the problem is "impossible." You don't ask Oracle to write boilerplate; you ask Oracle to solve the architectural bottleneck or debug the race condition that no one else can find.
// **Why Gemini 3 Pro?**
// This is the smartest model in your arsenal. Gemini 3 Pro brings **state-of-the-art reasoning** capabilities. It excels at "grounding" — checking facts against reality (or the provided context) rather than hallucinating. When you need a second opinion that carries weight, or when you need to analyze a screenshot of a UI bug alongside the code causing it, only Gemini's native multimodal high-IQ reasoning will suffice.
//  4. Prometheus: The Strategic Planner
// **Role:** Goal Decomposition, Roadmap Planning, "Deep Thought."
// **Model:** `arcee-ai/trinity-large-preview:free`
// Prometheus sits above the code. He doesn't look at syntax errors; he looks at the *goal*. If you say "Build a blog," Prometheus breaks it down into database schema, API design, and frontend components.
// **Why Trinity Large?**
// The Arcee "Trinity" model is designed for **synthetic reasoning** and merging different capabilities. Prometheus needs a model that can simulate the future — "If I plan this step first, what will go wrong later?" Trinity Large Preview offers the parameter density required for this kind of abstract, multi-step planning without getting bogged down in the implementation details immediately.
//  5. Momus: The Creative Critic
// **Role:** Satire, Code Review, Personality, "The Jester."
// **Model:** `minimax/minimax-m2.5`
// Momus is the harsh code reviewer who makes fun of your lack of comments, but also the creative writer who generates witty commit messages or engaging documentation.
// **Why Minimax?**
// Minimax models are renowned for their **high "EQ" (Emotional Quotient)** and roleplay ability. While other models strive to be robotic and neutral, Minimax excels at adopting personas. This makes it perfect for Momus, who requires a distinct voice to deliver criticism effectively (and entertainingly) or to write documentation that humans actually want to read.
//  6. Explore: The High-Speed Scout
// **Role:** Codebase Grep, Quick Lookups, File Discovery.
// **Model:** `x-ai/grok-4.1-fast`
// Explore is the intern running on caffeine. You tell it "Find where the user ID is defined," and it tears through 50 files in seconds. It doesn't need to understand the philosophy of the code; it just needs to find the string.
// **Why Grok Fast?**
// Speed is the only metric that matters here. **Grok 4.1 Fast** is engineered for low-latency inference. Using a heavy model like Gemini Pro or GLM for simple file searching is a waste of compute and time. Grok fires off queries, gets the paths, and returns immediately, allowing the smarter agents to do the actual work.
// ---
//  Model Families & Strengths
//  The Logic Family (Zhipu AI)
// *   **Model:** `z-ai/glm-4.7`
// *   **Best for:** Orchestration, Logic Puzzles, Strict JSON output.
// *   **Why:** GLM models act as the "Left Brain" of the system. They are less likely to drift creatively and more likely to follow strict algorithmic instructions.
//  The Context Family (Moonshot AI)
// *   **Model:** `moonshotai/kimi-k2.5`
// *   **Best for:** Coding, Large Refactors, Documentation reading.
// *   **Why:** Kimi acts as the "Memory" of the system. Its ability to handle massive tokens means it can ingest entire libraries of documentation before writing a single line of code.
//  The Visionary Family (Google)
// *   **Models:** `gemini-3-pro-preview`, `gemini-3-flash-preview`
// *   **Best for:** Visual Engineering, Complex Reasoning, Multimodal analysis.
// *   **Why:** Google's Gemini series is natively multimodal. It doesn't just "see" images; it reasons about them. Use Pro for hard problems and Flash for quick visual checks.
//  The Creative Family (Minimax & Arcee)
// *   **Models:** `minimax-m2.5`, `trinity-large-preview`
// *   **Best for:** Writing, Planning, Roleplay, Abstract thought.
// *   **Why:** These models represent the "Right Brain." They are less rigid than GLM and offer more creative, human-like, or abstract reasoning paths.
// ---
